body:
This PR makes modifying the COW state a little easier by returning a handle that allows you to make/chain multiple modifications. This allows us to modify the COW state from outside the `db_state.rs` file, which was becoming saddled with increasingly complex app logic.

The usage pattern is now:

```rs
let mut guard = self.db_inner.state.write();
guard.modify(|modifier| {
  // make modifications to the state accessed via
  // the modifier.state
});
```

The `modify` method ensure the state is copied on write when the modify block ends.

The motivation for this PR is that while implementing #685 I needed to make some modifications to the COWDbState but I didn't want to pipe details into the `db_state.rs` file that it really has no business knowing about.

during the implementation of #688, I came across the following code where the term snapshot appears to be overloaded after `DbSnapshot` introduced:

```
    pub async fn get_with_options<K: AsRef<[u8]>>(
        &self,
        key: K,
        options: &ReadOptions,
    ) -> Result<Option<Bytes>, SlateDBError> {
        self.db_stats.get_requests.inc();
        self.check_error()?;
        let snapshot = self.state.read().snapshot();
        self.reader
            .get_with_options(key, options, &snapshot, None)
            .await
    }
```

this PR tries to rename `self.state.read().snapshot()` to `self.state.read().view()` to  represent "a consistent view of the database state" and avoid naming conflicts with the "DbSnapshot" concept.

i am still a bit debating if `DbStateView` and `DbStateReader` here are better naming though.. any feedback is appreciated!
